rope":"Normandie, Europe","of LaBruce, Normandie Province, France":"Francie","Papa Stronsay, Orkney, Scotland":"Papa Stronsay, Orkney, Scotland"},"da":{"about 1028–1094":"omkring 1028–1094","1028–1094":"1028–1094","1029–1094":"1029–1094","1062–Male":"1062–Afdød","1011–1046":"1011–1046","1015–Female":"1015–Afdød","1029":"1029","1028":"1028","about 1062":"omkring 1062","1015":"1015","about 1028":"omkring 1028","1046":"1046","1011":"1011","1062":"1062","1094":"1094","Normandie, Europe":"Normandie, Europe","of LaBruce, Normandie Province, France":"Frankrig","Papa Stronsay, Orkney, Scotland":"Papa Stronsay, Orkney, Skotland"},"nl":{"about 1028–1094":"circa 1028–1094","1028–1094":"1028–1094","1029–1094":"1029–1094","1062–Male":"1062–Overleden","1011–1046":"1011–1046","1015–Female":"1015–Overleden","1029":"1029","1028":"1028","about 1062":"circa 1062","1015":"1015","about 1028":"circa 1028","1046":"1046","1011":"1011","1062":"1062","1094":"1094","Normandie, Europe":"Normandie, Europa","of LaBruce, Normandie Province, France":"Frankrijk","Papa Stronsay, Orkney, Scotland":"Papa Stronsay, Orkney, Schotland"},"en":{"about 1028–1094":"about 1028–1094","1028–1094":"1028–1094","1029–1094":"1029–1094","1062–Male":"1062–Deceased","1011–1046":"1011–1046","1015–Female":"1015–Deceased","1029":"1029","1028":"1028","about 1062":"about 1062","1015":"1015","about 1028":"about 1028","1046":"1046","1011":"1011","1062":"1062","1094":"1094","Normandie, Europe":"Normandie, Europe","of LaBruce, Normandie Province, France":"France","Papa Stronsay, Orkney, Scotland":"Papa Stronsay, Orkney, Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"De","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Bruce","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish (of Norman origin): habitational name from a place in Normandy, probably from Brix (La Manche).","Altered form of French   Brousse  .","History: The son of the Domesday baron, a friend of David I of Scotland, was granted by him the Lordship of Annandale in 1124, and his second son Robert became the founder of the Scottish house of Bruce. — This surname (see 2 above) is listed along with its original form <i>Brousse</i> in the (US) National Huguenot Society's register of qualified Huguenot ancestors."],"variants":[{"name":"Brousse","meanings":["(2010: NA)","French: topographic name for someone living in a scrubby area, from Old French <i>bro(u)ce</i> ‘thicket, brushwood’ (from Late Latin <i>bruscia</i>), or a habitational name from any of several places in France named Brousse. Compare   Bruce   and   Brusse  .","History: This surname is listed in the (US) National Huguenot Society's register of qualified Huguenot ancestors (along with its altered form <i>Bruce</i>) and also in the similar register of the Huguenot Society of South Carolina."]},{"name":"Brewis","meanings":["English:","(of Norman origin): habitational name from Briouze in Orne.","(Northumberland and Durham): topographic name or nickname from Middle English <i>breuhous</i> ‘brewery’ (literally ‘brew house’)."]}]},{"name":"Robart","type":"FIRST","meanings":["A name derived from the Old German, Ruadpert, Ruopreht, from rat-brecht, illustrious in counsel or illustrious councillor. The nicknames are Rob, Bob, Bobby, Hobb, Dobb, Dobbie, Dobby."],"variants":[{"name":"Rob","meanings":["Short form of   Robert   or other names with this first syllable."]},{"name":"Bob","meanings":["Altered short form of   Robert  , a later development than the common medieval forms <i>Hob</i>, <i>Dob</i>, and <i>Nob</i>, all of which, unlike <i>Bob</i>, have given rise to English surnames."]},{"name":"Dobbie","meanings":["A name derived from the Old German, Ruadpert, Ruopreht, from rat-brecht, illustrious in counsel or illustrious councillor. The nicknames are Rob, Bob, Bobby, Hobb, Dobb, Dobbie, Dobby."]},{"name":"Hobb","meanings":["A name derived from the Old German, Ruadpert, Ruopreht, from rat-brecht, illustrious in counsel or illustrious councillor. The nicknames are Rob, Bob, Bobby, Hobb, Dobb, Dobbie, Dobby."]},{"name":"Bobby","meanings":["Pet form of   Robert   (for its development,  see  Bob  ), now also used as an independent given name. It is also sometimes used as a girl's name, as a variant spelling of   Bobbie ."]},{"name":"Dobb","meanings":["A name derived from the Old German, Ruadpert, Ruopreht, from rat-brecht, illustrious in counsel or illustrious councillor. The nicknames are Rob, Bob, Bobby, Hobb, Dobb, Dobbie, Dobby."]},{"name":"Dobby","meanings":["A name derived from the Old German, Ruadpert, Ruopreht, from rat-brecht, illustrious in counsel or illustrious councillor. The nicknames are Rob, Bob, Bobby, Hobb, Dobb, Dobbie, Dobby."]}]},{"name":"or","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Oswald   or any of the various other names beginning with <i>Os-</i>."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Robart or Robert De Bruce was born about 1028, in France, his father, Regenwald Brusseson, was 19 and his mother, Arlogia Waldamar, was 15. He had at least 1 son with Emma De Brittany. He died in 1094, at the age of 67."},"et":{"about 1028–1094":"umbes 1028–1094","1028–1094":"1028–1094","1029–1094":"1029–1094","1062–Male":"1062–Surnud","1011–1046":"1011–1046","1015–Female":"1015–Surnud","1029":"1029","1028":"1028","about 1062":"umbes 1062","1015":"1015","about 1028":"umbes 1028","1046":"1046","1011":"1011","1062":"1062","1094":"1094","Normandie, Europe":"Normandie, Europe","of LaBruce, Normandie Province, France":"Prantsusmaa","Papa Stronsay, Orkney, Scotland":"Papa Stronsay, Orkney, Scotland"},"fi":{"about 1028–1094":"noin 1028–1094","1028–1094":"1028–1094","1029–1094":"1029–1094","1062–Male":"1062–Kuollut","1011–1046":"1011–1046","1015–Female":"1015–Kuollut","1029":"1029","1028":"1028","about 1062":"noin 1062","1015":"1015","about 1028":"noin 1028","1046":"1046","1011":"1011","1062":"1062","1094":"1094","Normandie, Europe":"Normandie, Europe","of LaBruce, Normandie Province, France":"Ranska","Papa Stronsay, Orkney, Scotland":"Papa Stronsay, Orkney, Scotland"},"fr":{"about 1028–1094":"environ 1028–1094","1028–1094":"1028–1094","1029–1094":"1029–1094","1062–Male":"1062–Décédé","1011–1046":"1011–1046","1015–Female":"1015–Décédée",